--- title: Dealing with mic pops in recordings author: Josef Fruehwald layout: post category: blogpost tags: - audio - phonetics - methods ---

I've been working on a project to improve the audio quality of archival recordings, and one of the problems I had was both fieldworkers and interviewees not being gentle with the microphones. There are many loud pops that make it challenging to normalize the volume, and some of the downstream noise reduction methods I used had a tendency to accentuate these pops even further.

I stumbled upon a solution of using a method implemented in the librosa library that decomposes spectrograms into their harmonic and percussive components. Most of the documentation is written focusing on separating drum tracks from their audio, but with some modification I found it worked really well for squashing my mic pops!

Harmonic percussive decomposition¶

While trying to figure out how to address the issue of these pops and browsing through the documentation for the librosa library, I found a tutorial on harmonic-percussive decomposition. The tutorial and background literature seems to be mostly focused on extracting drums and rhythm from music tracks, but it struck me that I could possibly use this to target and minimize these pops.

The procedure has the following steps.

  1. Calculate the short term fourier transform of the audio (with librosa.stft())
  2. Decompise the spectrum into the harmonic and percussive components (with librosa.decompose.hpss)
  3. Be sure to calculate the residual spectrum of information that was in neither then harmonic nor percussive spectrum (just using subtraction).
  4. Separate the percussive spectrum into separate magnitude and phase components (with librosa.magphase()).
  5. Convert the magnitude spectrum to a decibel spectrum (with librosa.amplitude_to_db())
  6. Subtract 20, or some other number, of decibels from the decibel spectrum (with subtraction)
  7. Convert the decibel spectrum back to magnitude (with librosa.db_to_amplitude())
  8. Recombine this new pecussive amplitude spectrum with the original phase component (with multiplication)
  9. Combine this new percussive spectrum with the original harmonic and redidual components (with addition)
  10. Convert the new combined spectrum back into a signal (with librosa.istft())

Here are some things I've found to be important

Use a relatively short window length in the first short term fourier transform settings.¶

To begin with, we need to get a short term fourier spectrum, which has a number of different parameters including the how fine grained you want your frequency resolution to be (n_fft), how narrow you want the analysis window to be (win_length), and how small of a hop you want the analysis window to make (hop_length). You can have a larger number for n_fft than win_length, and librosa will pad the window out with 0s.

Librosa recommends using values of n_fft, win_length and hop_length that are some powers of 2. So the default n_fft (which I stick to) is 2048 which is $2^{11}$. However, this corresponds to a pretty long time window at the sampling rate of 16,000, so I use a window length of 512, and a hop length of 128. When I tried using longer windows, I wasn't able to isolate the pops very effectively.

Use a large margin for the percussive component¶

To be honest, I don't fully understand how the harmonic-percussive decomposition works, but the documentation says to use a larger number for the "margin" if you want to be more selective about what gets included into the harmonic or percussive spectrums. Since we're going to be decreasing the loudness of the percussive spectrum by a lot, and because there are some percussive components to speech, we'll want to pretty strongly selective about what gets into the percussive spectrum, thus give it a large margin.

The Actual Process.¶

Step 1: Calculate the short term fourier transform¶

Like I said above, I'm using a pretty narrow window of 512 samples, which at a sampling rate of 16,000 corresponds to 32 miliseconds of audio.

In [5]:
S = librosa.stft(wav, n_fft = 2048, win_length = 512, hop_length=512//4)
# Getting the decibel spectrum for plotting below
S_db = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(S))

Steps 2 and 3: Do the harmonic-percussive decomposition, and get the residual¶

I'm passing the argument margin a tuple with values (1.0, 5.0). The first value is the margin for the harmonic component, which we're not going to be choosy about, and the second value is for the percussive component, which are are going to be choosy about. For this specific example, I found a value of about 5 to be the sweet spot.

Some components of the original spectrogram are included in neither the harmonic nor the percussive component, so we'll want to capture that for when we reconstruct the sound at the end.

In [6]:
S_harm, S_perc = librosa.decompose.hpss(S, margin = (1.0, 5.0))
S_resid = S - (S_harm + S_perc)

Here's the four spectrograms compared directly:

Step 4: Get the mangitude & phase of the percussive spectrogram¶

The S_perc matrix contains complex values which correspond to the magnitude of the fft components and the phase of the fft components. We want to reduce the magnutude, but leave the phase alone, so we'll separate them into separate matrices.

In [8]:
S_perc_mag, S_perc_phase = librosa.magphase(S_perc)

Step 5 and 6: Working in decibels¶

I just find it easier to think about and describe the next steps in terms of "subtracting 20 db from the percussive component", so I convert the magnitude spectrum to decibelsm and subtract 20.

In [9]:
S_perc_mag_db = librosa.amplitude_to_db(S_perc_mag)
S_perc_mag_damp = S_perc_mag_db - 20

Step 7 and 8: Back to amplitude and complex spectrum¶

We can convert this new, quieter percussive spectrum back to a magnitude spectrum, then recombine with the phase information we pulled out in step 4.

In [10]:
S_perc_mag_damp_amp = librosa.db_to_amplitude(S_perc_mag_damp)
S_perc_new = S_perc_mag_damp_amp * S_perc_phase

Step 9 and 10: Back to a signal¶

Next step is to create a new spectrogram by adding together the original harmonic spectrogram, the new quieter percussive spectrogram, and the resdual components. Then, we can convert this spectrogram back into a signal with the inverse fourier transform.

(Be sure to use the same n_fft, win_length and hop_length values you did when you created the original spectrogram, or else it will sound really weird!)

In [11]:
S_out = S_harm + S_perc_new + S_resid
signal_out = librosa.istft(S_out, n_fft = 2048, win_length = 512, hop_length=512//4)
signal_norm = librosa.util.normalize(signal_out)

The results¶

If we just look at the waveforms of before and after, we can just visually see how we've tamped down those mic pops.

In [12]:
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [8, 8]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,  1)
img = librosa.display.waveshow(wav,
                               sr = sr,
                               ax = ax[0])
ax[0].set(title='Original Signal')
ax[0].label_outer()    
img2 = librosa.display.waveshow(signal_norm,
                               sr = sr,
                               ax = ax[1])
ax[1].set(title='New Signal')
ax[1].label_outer() 
plt.show()
plt.close()

And the result sounds pretty good too!

So, we've achieved the most important thing, which is being able to normalize the volume of the audio, and now the speakers' voices aren't being overwhelmed by the mic pops!
